-- V45: Update interface node_type_documentation to fix description and align with current blocking/non-blocking behavior
SET search_path TO orchestrator;

UPDATE node_type_documentation
SET description = 'Interface node: visual HTML template connected to a workflow. ALWAYS provide all 3 templates when creating: html_template, css_template, js_template. Use CSS classes (no inline style="..."). Use js_template for conditional display and dynamic behavior. ONLY {{variable}} and {{variable|default}} are supported - NEVER use {{#if}}, {{#each}}, {{else}}, {{/if}} (NOT Handlebars). EXECUTION: If action_mapping contains __continue, the interface is BLOCKING - registers an INTERFACE_SIGNAL and the workflow stays RUNNING until the user clicks __continue. If NO __continue in action_mapping, the interface is NON-BLOCKING - returns success() immediately and successors execute at once. The interface stays clickable in both cases. 3 USAGE PATTERNS: (A) DISPLAY: variable_mapping binds template variables to workflow data. No action_mapping needed. Non-blocking. (B) APPLICATION: action_mapping binds forms/buttons to triggers → user submits → trigger fires → workflow runs → results displayed (loop). The interface is both the END (displays results) and the START (fires trigger for next cycle). (C) MULTI-PAGE APP: multiple interface nodes + navigate actions to switch between pages. Create the template first with interface(action=''create'') using generic {{variable|default}} syntax. IMPORTANT: Interface nodes MUST be connected in the DAG - they are regular nodes with incoming edges, NOT standalone. An interface can only fire triggers from its OWN DAG (never another DAG). isEntryInterface controls which interface tab is shown first in Application Mode and which interface the frontend auto-returns to after workflow completion. Place the entry interface early in the DAG for a visual flow that matches the user journey.',
    concepts = E'["BLOCKING vs NON-BLOCKING: Determined by __continue in action_mapping. With __continue → BLOCKING: workflow stays RUNNING, epoch stays open, DAG waits until user clicks __continue. Without __continue → NON-BLOCKING: node returns success() immediately, successors execute, interface stays clickable but does not block workflow.", "BLOCKING INTERFACE (__continue): Workflow reaches interface → pauses (RUNNING, epoch stays open) → user interacts → clicks __continue → signal resolves → workflow resumes to next node. Use for wizards, approval forms, multi-step flows.", "NON-BLOCKING INTERFACE (no __continue): Workflow reaches interface → completes immediately → successors execute → interface stays displayed and clickable. Buttons fire triggers (new epochs). Use for dashboards, interactive apps, display-only pages.", "APPLICATION PATTERN (interactive loop): Interface has action_mapping pointing to a trigger in the same DAG. User sees entry interface → fills form → submits (action_mapping fires trigger) → trigger creates new epoch → workflow re-executes → results displayed on downstream interfaces via variable_mapping → frontend auto-returns to entry interface → user interacts again (loop). BEST PRACTICE: Place the entry interface early in the DAG (typically after the trigger) for a visual flow that matches the user journey. The frontend automatically navigates back to the entry interface when the workflow completes.", "ACTION MAPPING WIRING: CSS selector in action_mapping must match an HTML element. Any valid CSS selector works (#id, .class, element.class). Bridge script uses querySelectorAll(selector). If no element matches, the binding is silently skipped (no error). Alternative: use data-action=\\"name\\" attribute on elements instead of CSS selectors - the bridge also checks querySelectorAll(''[data-action=name]'').", "SAME-DAG RULE: An interface can ONLY fire triggers within its own DAG. All trigger references in action_mapping MUST belong to the SAME DAG as the interface. For multiple actions (search, delete, refresh), create multiple triggers within the same DAG.", "ENTRY INTERFACE: isEntryInterface=true determines which interface tab is shown first in Application Mode. The entry interface MUST be connected in the DAG like any other node - it is NOT standalone/orphaned. Place it early in the DAG for visual clarity. Only one interface should be marked entry; if multiple are marked, first in plan order is used. When the workflow completes, the frontend automatically navigates back to the entry interface.", "NAVIGATE ACTION: interface:label:navigate switches the displayed interface tab (frontend-only, no backend call). Target must be in the same workflow but does NOT need to be in the same DAG (unlike trigger actions). Use for multi-page layouts.", "WIZARD PATTERN: Chain interfaces directly in the DAG: interface:page_1 → interface:page_2 → interface:page_3 → mcp:process. Each has __continue (blocking). Workflow stays RUNNING throughout - no run reopening needed. Each interface waits for user, then advances.", "SPLIT + INTERFACE (CAROUSEL): When interface follows a Split node, SplitAwareNodeExecutor executes the interface once per item. Each item gets its own signal and step_data entry. Frontend displays as paginated carousel. Each __continue only resolves its own item signal.", "COMBINED ACTIONS: A single interface can have BOTH regular actions AND __continue. Example: {#search-form: trigger:search:submit, #done-btn: __continue}. User can submit searches multiple times (fires trigger, signal stays active), then click Done (__continue) to advance the DAG.", "EDGE FORMAT: Interfaces use interface: prefix. { from: trigger:start, to: interface:customer_form }. No ports (interfaces are linear, not branching). Plan array: interfaces[] (separate from triggers/mcps/cores/agents).", "INTERFACE OUTPUTS: Action data is persisted and accessible downstream via SpEL: {{interface:label.output.action_name.field_name}}. Example: {{interface:my_form.output.submit.email}} returns the email submitted via the form.", "FORK + INTERFACE: When an interface is in a Fork branch, it executes in parallel with other branches. Non-blocking interface: branch completes immediately. Blocking interface: workflow stays RUNNING until user fires __continue. Other branches execute normally. Multiple blocking interfaces in parallel (e.g. after a Fork) = workflow waits until ALL are resolved.", "RUN REOPENING (non-blocking with successors): If a non-blocking interface has successors in the DAG, the workflow may COMPLETE before the user interacts. If the signal is later resolved (e.g. via REST API), SignalResumeService reopens the COMPLETED run (sets status=RUNNING), executes successors, then re-finalizes to COMPLETED.", "EPOCH BROWSING: Each trigger fire creates a new epoch. Previous epoch results remain in the database and are browsable in the interface carousel. The InterfaceRenderService paginates on (epoch, spawn, itemIndex) triples - users can navigate between results from different executions."]'::jsonb,
    parameters = E'{"showPreview": {"type": "boolean", "default": true, "required": false, "description": "Show live preview on the workflow builder canvas"}, "interface_id": {"type": "uuid", "required": true, "description": "UUID from interface(action=''create'')"}, "action_mapping": {"type": "object", "required": false, "description": "Binds HTML elements to workflow triggers or navigation via CSS selectors. Format: {\\"#css-selector\\": \\"target\\"}. Any valid CSS selector works (#id, .class, element.class). Targets: trigger:label:submit (form - captures all <input name=...> fields), trigger:label:click (button - fires trigger, no data), trigger:label:message (chat input), interface:label:navigate (page switch, frontend-only), __continue (resolve signal, resume DAG - makes interface BLOCKING), __pagination:prev/__pagination:next (browse results). SAME-DAG RULE: All trigger references MUST belong to the SAME DAG as the interface."}, "isEntryInterface": {"type": "boolean", "default": false, "required": false, "description": "Mark as primary interface shown first in Application Mode. MUST still be connected in DAG - not standalone. At least one interface must be entry."}, "variable_mapping": {"type": "object", "required": false, "description": "DISPLAY: Map template variables to workflow data. {\\"title\\": \\"{{mcp:fetch.output.name}}\\"}"}}'::jsonb,
    examples = '["workflow_builder(action=''add_node'', type=''interface'', label=''Dashboard'', params={interface_id: ''<uuid>'', variable_mapping: {''title'': ''{{mcp:fetch.output.name}}'', ''status'': ''{{mcp:fetch.output.status}}''}}, connect_after=''FetchData'')", "workflow_builder(action=''add_node'', type=''interface'', label=''Contact Form'', params={interface_id: ''<uuid>'', variable_mapping: {''name'': ''{{mcp:get_user.output.name}}''}, action_mapping: {''#contact-form'': ''trigger:contact_form:submit'', ''#done-btn'': ''__continue''}}, connect_after=''GetUser'')", "workflow_builder(action=''add_node'', type=''interface'', label=''Search App'', params={interface_id: ''<uuid>'', action_mapping: {''#search-form'': ''trigger:search:submit'', ''#delete-btn'': ''trigger:delete:click'', ''#refresh-btn'': ''trigger:refresh:click''}, isEntryInterface: true}, connect_after=''Init'')"]'::jsonb,
    updated_at = NOW()
WHERE type = 'interface';
